<br>
 &quot;Ignorants.... ignorants.... silly cuty lilly frowny stinky baby both y'ar...&quot;<br>
<br>
 *sitting a bit straighter, he allowed a large smile to form on his face*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Both of you speak as if hatred, anger, sadism, pain and others were decisions one would do.... ignorant ignoramus ignoratibus...&quot;<br>
<br>
 *he stood slowly on the table, sweeping some dust off his sleeves*<br>
<br>
 &quot;hatred, anger, sadness, pain, fear and all are powers. just like love, care, compassion and all other feelings are.&quot;<br>
<br>
 *the gnome wiggled his fingers, small bubbles of yellow-greenish power escaping them, and soon was he surrounded by the energy, it only dissipating to reveal a tier'dal wearing the gnome's robes albeit suiting him size-ways*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Hatred.... i hate you.... koada'dals are what we were born from, they were the ones that didn't have to endure our tortures, the godly and horrible pains that were inflicted to us. Why us and not you? Why did you escape such horrors? Why were you the ones walking the paths of Norrath when we were cast underground in our caves?&quot;<br>
<br>
 *the gnome returned to his normal shape, arching an eyebrow*<br>
<br>
 &quot;The hatred felt so is but a common feeling. It lives in any species, following or not the god of hate. It comes from Fate, from whatever tricks lady Fortuna played on such or such race. Did the tier'dals decide to be hateful? Was it a path they have chosen to follow? <br>
 No, it was bred in their bones, they would say.<br>
 Nincompop!&quot;<br>
<br>
 *Rasslyn shifted from one foot to the other, frowning*<br>
<br>
 &quot;It was not more bred in their souls than it was in any other species! it is in everyone's blood, but some cultures show it more than others! how dare ye say, as the tier'dal here expressed, that you shall feel no hatred for the one that dishonoured your daughter against her will? that slaughtered your newborn child in the most atrocious ways? You shall feel hatred. For this hatred we all share and know.&quot;<br>
<br>
 *the small gnome then turned into a troll, his eyes gleaming with a dark somber light*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Fear.... we were born from fear.... we felt the hunger, each a day, each a moment, terrible hunger that would torture our innards, drive us to insanity. We needed to feed, to eat, to consume! Small races came, they couldn't defend themselves.... it was survival for the fittest, we won and we ate! But you consider us monsters, you consider us criminals, why? You kill us for territory, we kill you for food, how are we different? We cast fear on you, but tis no choice of ours! We were born this way, casting shadows and dspair in your heart, but we didn't choose to, we were made as such, as barbarians were made tall and halfling hairy!&quot;<br>
<br>
 *Once more did the gnome return to his former self, grinning*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Have trolls decided to bring fear in the name of their original creator, Cazic-Thule? Or was fear a feeling that existed in all species since the beginning, and that awoke when smaller and more vulnerable ones saw such hulking creatures surpassing their power by far, and even before each a time they were surpassed by anyone? The fear of the hunted in front of the predator? <br>
 And why are trolls now afraid, now the hunted ones? Should they not, in Cazic-Thule's name, be the ones bringing fear only?<br>
 No, they were born with fear in them, just as we all, all species, and fear they knew when they turned into being the tracked ones. There is no such things as being spawns of the god of fear.&quot;<br>
<br>
 *the small gnome then turned into a human, grabbing the knife that was resting on the table he stood on, and saluting people in a knightly way*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Honor. We must respect honor and law, for they are the only things to guide us, the light that shine and we follow. Without Honor, we return to being savage beings, to the darkest moments of our history.<br>
 Honor is to be followed, and there is no such thing as hating, fearing, dominating or anything else. Follow Honor, for only it is right.&quot;<br>
<br>
 *once more, -POOF- back to gnomishness*<br>
<br>
 &quot;Honor? Why would only followers of Mithaniel be born with this? Were the first humans all honourable? Have the other species not following their gods shown no hnor?<br>
 Trolls show honor in their wars, Ogres also, the proud followers of Rallos Zek. How come, since they do not walk the path of Honor? How come tier'dals would follow the rules of war when they are but hateful spawns of Innoruuk? Why thieves of Bristlebane sometimes spare someone that fought bravely?<br>
 Honor was not bred in the humans souls. Honor is a value that all species share, but that their cultures decide or not to show. Honor is, and is followed or not, whatever your skin, height or god is. Deal with it. And anyhow, if followers of Mithaniel Marr were but honor incarnated, why are those frogs utterly insane and fanatics? Did they exclusively follow the rules of honor when kickin the trolls out of Grobb?<br>
 No, they fought, they won, they slaughtered. As anyone else, Mithaniel spawn or not.&quot;<br>
<br>
 *the gnome took a second of rest, drinking some stout to wetten up his parched throat*<br>
<br>
 &quot;God of Fear, god of Hate, god of Honor, and all the other gods.... they are greater beings, aye, but they are not the origin of whatever their title say. No. They incarnate the idea, yes, but that doesn't make them exclusive owners of such feelings and ideas.<br>
 The god of fear rules over human and gnome hearts also, the Mother of all Tunare reigns also on trolls, Terris and Morell respectively reign also on dreams and nightmare by their decisions.<br>
 There is no such thing as feelings being exclusive to one race. All those ideas we follow, war, power, hatred and such, we all share them since the beginning, since the Nameless one. Is the nameless one a god to follow even? no, it is a power, a billowing magma of energies that once gave birth to the world.<br>
 So please stop saying you can fight hatred. You cannot, for even at least once you will feel it. Tier'dals with always know love at least once, iksars will feel the need for honor as well, and so on. Gods are but representations of what part of the common pool of feelings and ideas a race, by it's culture, decided to consider the most important, the most powerful.<br>
<br>
 And anyhow, if gods are as you say, whya re you speaking about love, hatred and such wth Tunare? She is no goddess of love or righteousness. Nature gives, Nature takes. Nature doesn't have feelings, Nature breeds and gives death, there is no love, honor, respect or whatsoever with Nature and Tunare. It's survival of the fittest... wich quite puts you at the same place than every SINGLE race of Norrath...<br>
<br>
 Welcome to the world, elf.&quot;<br>
<br>
 *with this did the gnome sit again on his chair, drinking his stout and ordering some more, scribbling furiously on a notepad*<br>
<br>
 <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Rasslyn the shym</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
